## 5. Firebase Firestore Data Model

### Collection Structure

```
firestore/
├── teachers/{teacherId}
│   ├── name, phone, email, slug, bio
│   ├── subjects[], location, photo, isVerified
│   ├── plan: 'free' | 'pro'
│   └── createdAt, updatedAt
│
├── students/{studentId}
│   ├── teacherId (owner)
│   ├── name, phone, parentPhone, grade, address
│   ├── isArchived: boolean
│   └── createdAt
│
├── batches/{batchId}
│   ├── teacherId
│   ├── name, subject, schedule: {days[], time, duration}
│   ├── feesPerMonth, maxSeats, currentSeats (counter)
│   ├── status: 'active' | 'paused' | 'closed'
│   └── term: string (e.g., "2024-Q1")
│
├── enrollments/{enrollmentId}          ← Junction: Student ↔ Batch
│   ├── teacherId, studentId, batchId
│   ├── enrolledAt, leftAt (null if active)
│   └── isActive: boolean
│
├── attendance/{attendanceId}           ← Keyed: batchId_date
│   ├── teacherId, batchId, date (YYYY-MM-DD)
│   ├── records: { [studentId]: 'present' | 'absent' | 'holiday' }
│   └── markedAt
│
├── feeRecords/{feeRecordId}
│   ├── teacherId, studentId, batchId
│   ├── amount, dueDate, month (YYYY-MM)
│   ├── status: 'pending' | 'partial' | 'paid' | 'overdue'
│   ├── paidAmount, paidAt, paymentMode: 'cash'|'upi'|'cheque'|'other'
│   └── memo: string (optional)
│
├── notes/{noteId}
│   ├── teacherId, batchId (null = all batches)
│   ├── title, subject, storageUrl, fileType
│   └── uploadedAt
│
├── tests/{testId}
│   ├── teacherId, batchId
│   ├── title, subject, date, totalMarks, type: 'online' | 'offline'
│   ├── questions[]: [{text, options[], correct, marks}]  (online only)
│   └── pdfUrl: string (offline only)
│
├── testResults/{resultId}
│   ├── testId, studentId, teacherId
│   ├── score, maxScore, submittedAt
│   └── answers: {} (online only)
│
├── announcements/{announcementId}
│   ├── teacherId, targetBatchId (null = all)
│   ├── title, message, channels: ['inapp', 'whatsapp']
│   ├── isPinned: boolean
│   └── scheduledAt, sentAt
│
└── leads/{leadId}
    ├── teacherId, name, phone, grade, message
    ├── status: 'new' | 'contacted' | 'enrolled' | 'rejected'
    └── receivedAt
```

### Firestore Indexes Required

```yaml
# Composite indexes (must pre-create)
students: [teacherId ASC, isArchived ASC, createdAt DESC]
enrollments: [teacherId ASC, batchId ASC, isActive ASC]
attendance: [teacherId ASC, batchId ASC, date DESC]
feeRecords: [teacherId ASC, status ASC, dueDate ASC]
feeRecords: [teacherId ASC, studentId ASC, month DESC]
leads: [teacherId ASC, status ASC, receivedAt DESC]
```

---

## 6. Redis Caching Strategy

```
Cache Topology: Single Redis instance (MVP) → Redis Cluster (scale)

┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Key Pattern              │  TTL    │  What's cached         │
├───────────────────────────┼─────────┼───────────────────────┤
│  dashboard:{teacherId}    │  5 min  │  KPI summary object    │
│  attendance:{batchId}:{M} │  1 hr   │  Monthly % per student │
│  report:fees:{teacherId}  │  1 hr   │  Fee collection totals │
│  report:tests:{batchId}   │  2 hr   │  Test averages         │
│  profile:public:{slug}    │  15 min │  Public profile page   │
│  session:{userId}         │  24 hr  │  Firebase token + role │
└───────────────────────────┴─────────┴───────────────────────┘

Cache Invalidation:
  - On any write to attendance → invalidate attendance:{batchId}:*
  - On fee marked paid → invalidate dashboard:{teacherId}, report:fees:{teacherId}
  - On profile update → invalidate profile:public:{slug}
  - Use event emitter in service layer to trigger invalidation
```

---

## 7. Data Flow Diagrams

### 7.1 Teacher Marks Attendance

```
Teacher (UI)
  │  POST /api/v1/attendance/:batchId
  ▼
Next.js API Route (Edge Middleware)
  │  Verify Firebase ID Token → Extract teacherId
  ▼
Node.js Attendance Controller
  │  Validate: batchId belongs to teacherId, date is valid
  ▼
Attendance Service
  │  Upsert document: attendance/{batchId}_{date}
  ▼
Attendance Repository
  │  Firestore batch write (atomic)
  ▼
Redis Cache Invalidation
  │  DEL attendance:{batchId}:{YYYY-MM}
  ▼
Response: 200 OK → UI updates optimistically
```

### 7.2 Student Submits Lead from Public Profile

```
Student (Public Profile Page)
  │  POST /api/v1/leads  (no auth required — rate-limited by IP)
  ▼
Next.js API Route
  │  Rate check: max 3 leads/IP/hour (Redis counter)
  ▼
Node.js Leads Controller
  │  Validate: name, phone, teacherId
  ▼
Leads Service
  │  Write to leads/{leadId}
  ▼
Firestore
  │  Triggers Firestore onWrite hook
  ▼
Cloud Function (Firebase)
  │  Sends in-app notification to teacher dashboard
  ▼
Teacher Dashboard (polling/SSE)
  │  "New Lead" badge appears
```

### 7.3 Teacher Generates Fee Records

```
Teacher
  │  POST /api/v1/fees/generate  { batchId, amount, dueDate, month }
  ▼
Fees Controller → Fees Service
  │  1. Fetch active enrollments for batchId
  │  2. Filter: skip students with existing record for this month
  │  3. Batch-create feeRecords (Firestore batch write, max 500/batch)
  ▼
Firestore (feeRecords collection)
  │  N new documents created
  ▼
Redis Invalidation
  │  DEL dashboard:{teacherId}, DEL report:fees:{teacherId}
  ▼
Response: { created: N, skipped: M }
```

---

## 8. Architecture Decision Records (ADRs)

### ADR-001: Modular Monolith over Microservices

| | |
|--|--|
| **Decision** | Single deployable Node.js backend with module boundaries |
| **Alternatives** | Microservices per module |
| **Rationale** | Team ≤ 5 devs, modules share teacher context, no independent scaling needed |
| **Consequence** | Module coupling risk → mitigated by strict interface contracts between modules |
| **Migration path** | Extract fees/reports as separate services if they hit scaling bottlenecks |

### ADR-002: Firestore over PostgreSQL

| | |
|--|--|
| **Decision** | Firebase Firestore as primary database |
| **Alternatives** | PostgreSQL (Supabase/Neon) |
| **Rationale** | Firebase Auth already chosen; Firestore = same ecosystem, no infra management, auto-scaling reads |
| **Risk** | Complex queries are harder; no JOINs |
| **Mitigation** | Denormalize strategically (counters in batch doc); aggregate in service layer |
| **Migration path** | Move to PostgreSQL if query complexity becomes blocking |

### ADR-003: Redis for Session + Hot Data

| | |
|--|--|
| **Decision** | Redis for session store + report caching |
| **Alternatives** | Firestore session doc, no-cache |
| **Rationale** | Report aggregations are expensive Firestore reads; cache cuts both cost and latency |
| **TTL policy** | Conservative: 5–120 min. Aggressive invalidation on write |

### ADR-004: ISR for Public Discovery Pages

| | |
|--|--|
| **Decision** | Next.js ISR (Incremental Static Regeneration) for /search and /teachers/[slug] |
| **Alternatives** | SSR on every request, CSR |
| **Rationale** | SEO critical + data changes infrequently (teacher profiles, not real-time) |
| **Revalidation** | 15 min for profiles; 1 hr for search index |
| **Trigger** | On-demand revalidation via Next.js `revalidatePath()` when teacher updates profile |

### ADR-005: No Built-in Payment Gateway

| | |
|--|--|
| **Decision** | Fee module is a tracking tool only — no Razorpay/Stripe integration |
| **Rationale** | Teachers use their own UPI; gateway adds compliance complexity for MVP |
| **Consequence** | Can add `paymentLinkUrl` field to feeRecords later for external links |
| **Future** | If demand exists → optional Razorpay module (behind Pro plan feature flag) |

---

## 9. Scaling Strategy

### Phase 1: Launch (0 → 1K teachers)
```
Infrastructure:
  - Next.js: Vercel (hobby → pro)
  - Node.js: Single instance (Railway / Fly.io)
  - Firestore: Default limits sufficient
  - Redis: Upstash (serverless, free tier)

Cost estimate: ~$20–50/month
Bottleneck: None expected at this scale
```

### Phase 2: Growth (1K → 10K teachers)
```
Changes:
  - Node.js: 2–3 instances behind load balancer
  - Redis: Standalone instance (Redis Cloud 100MB)
  - Add Firestore composite indexes for all query patterns
  - Implement proper error monitoring (Sentry)
  - Add DB connection pooling (Firebase Admin SDK pools by default)

Cost estimate: ~$100–300/month
Bottleneck watch: Report aggregation queries, Firestore read costs
```

### Phase 3: Scale (10K → 100K teachers)
```
Changes:
  - Extract Reports module as separate service (read-heavy, cacheable)
  - Add BullMQ queue for async jobs (fee reminders, bulk notifications)
  - Firestore: Review hot documents (teacher profile = add caching layer)
  - Redis Cluster for session distribution
  - Edge caching (Cloudflare) for public profiles
  - Consider BigQuery for analytics aggregations (Firestore → BigQuery export)

Cost estimate: ~$500–2000/month
Migration path trigger: P95 response time > 500ms on report endpoints
```

### Phase 4: Enterprise (100K+ teachers)
```
Changes:
  - Full CQRS for reports (separate read model)
  - Extract Notifications as event-driven service
  - Firebase → PostgreSQL migration for relational query needs
  - Kubernetes (GKE) for backend services
  - CDN + regional Firestore replicas
```

---

## 10. Security Architecture

```
Authentication:
  - Firebase Auth handles identity (email, phone OTP, Google OAuth)
  - Backend verifies Firebase ID Token on every request
  - Tokens expire every 1 hour; refresh handled by Firebase SDK

Authorization:
  - Role: teacher | admin | student (stored in Firebase Custom Claims)
  - Every API route checks: token.teacherId === resource.teacherId
  - Admin routes: separate middleware checking admin claim

Data Isolation:
  - Every Firestore query mandates teacherId filter
  - Firestore Security Rules as second layer (defense in depth)

Firestore Security Rules (simplified):
  match /students/{studentId} {
    allow read, write: if request.auth.token.teacherId == resource.data.teacherId;
  }

Rate Limiting:
  - Redis-based rate limiter on lead submission (IP: 3 req/hr)
  - Global: 100 req/min per authenticated user
  - Unauthenticated: 20 req/min per IP

Secrets:
  - All keys in environment variables (never in code)
  - Firebase Service Account key via secret manager (Google Secret Manager)
```

---

## Summary

| Layer | Technology | Pattern |
|-------|-----------|---------|
| Frontend | Next.js 14+ App Router | SSG + ISR (public) · CSR (dashboard) |
| API | Next.js Edge Middleware | Auth verification + proxy |
| Backend | Node.js (Express/Fastify) | Modular Monolith |
| Database | Firebase Firestore | Document store with denormalization |
| File Storage | Firebase Storage | Notes, avatars |
| Cache | Redis (Upstash MVP) | Session + hot data TTL cache |
| Auth | Firebase Auth | ID Token verification + Custom Claims |
| Hosting | Vercel (FE) + Railway/Fly (BE) | Managed PaaS |
